{"id":"math/0303295","submitter":"Avi Silterra","authors":"Mihai Tohaneanu, Margarethe Flanders, Avi Silterra","title":"C-Groups","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR math.CO","license":null,"abstract":"  In this paper we explore the structure and properties of C-groups. We define\na C-group as a group $G$ with $rk(G) < rk(Z(G))$ (where $rk(G)$ is the minimal\ncardinal of a generating set for a group $G$). Using GAP (a group theory\nprogram) and traditional methods, we identified an interesting infinite class\nof C-groups. In particular, we have proved that there is always a C-group of\norder an integer multiple of a fifth power of a prime. One way to obtain\nC-groups is take the direct product of certain C-groups, mentioned in this\npaper, with other appropriate groups. We, at this time, do not know whether the\nC-groups discussed in this paper are the building block of all finite C-groups.\nBut a complete classification of finite or infinite C-groups is an interesting\nproblem. We have also formulated a number of open questions relating to\nC-groups: Are they all solvable? What is the structure of the C-groups that are\nnot in our class? Is the minimal number of generators of the center always\npolynomially bounded by the minimal number of generators of the group? What are\nthe isoperimetric inequalities of infinite C-groups?\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 24 Mar 2003 20:36:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
